metadata.name: Emotional Shell #180
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 72 ¬∑ 54 ¬∑ 40 ¬∑ 30 ¬∑ 24 ¬∑ 20 every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted, and then drop one price tier.

---------

The feeling of being human ‚Äì with all of its intricate hopes, struggles, and fleeting emotions ‚Äì seems so unique that we assume artificial intelligence could never replicate our experience. And while we devise systems for solving unfathomably complex problems, generating algorithmic creativity, and unlocking regenerative biological possibilities, we simultaneously cling to the power and originality of emotional feeling ‚Äì believing it to be the irreplaceable source of what makes us human.

If the body is our shell for emotion and soul, can an artificial humanoid be another vessel for these thoughts and feelings ‚Äì for human essence itself? If our ‚Äòsoul‚Äô is the last stand between us and the machines, what happens when the soul becomes transferable? That we may see answers to these questions looks more real every year, and is perhaps a little frightening. 

Emotional Shell uses introspective portraits of future selves to question what it means to be human, when the people around us are no longer human.

metadata.name: Action; System #23
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of Fran√ßois Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------

metadata.name: intentions 02 #2
metadata.description:
The noise mechanism in intentions 01 is replaced with a descending random rectangle mechanism. Along the bottom, one can see the total number of slices, and the gradient created by the two colors used.

Traits:

Color 1 & Color 2: each chosen from its own pool of 10. Each color is equally likely.

Background: There is a 1-in-10 chance of getting an inverted intention. 

Slices: The number of slices in the stack, with 5 being the least likely.

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: Lost Twins #326
metadata.description:
Individually, the mints of this token are very simple. Each mint generates half of two cube forms, and each half is assigned random hues (in multiples of 10, from 0 to 360). Collectively as a project, this token challenges the approach of looking for "rarities" in a new way. How the cubes are rendered leaves the possibility for multiple mints to potentially join up on the sides with colors that perfect match each other. Will you find your lost twin?

Made in p5js
Created November 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: MOMENT #38
metadata.description:
An endless row of them making up each life. Some poignant, some inspiring, some grievous, some affirming - but most of them a tad boring, a bit generic, almost forgettable like bland fabric. How can a life constructed from such mundanity count for anything? Maybe thanks to the last one, the one that stitches them all together, like a punchline to an absurdist joke.

Generative art written in JavaScript + Canvas with a little bit of help from p5.js.
